The Eastern Desert is a vast arid waste east of Midgaard, formerly irrigated by the Iseth Reach river.
The Keepers of Measure governed it before any empire, using road stones calibrated to star angles, cistern basins, and water-right levies instead of coin.
The Twelve Obelisk Lines served as legal instruments: their shadows marked travel windows, ration days, and departure periods. Glyphs in Measure Script encoded direction, time, water volume, and legal status in one symbol.
Merchant houses transformed Keeper survey law into the Salt Ledger Kingdoms, hereditary rulers whose legitimacy depended on keeping routes open and cistern accounts balanced.
The charter road system connected oasis settlements to pyramid worksites and distant cities via charter stones bearing distance, toll rates, and witness seals.
When the Iseth Reach dried, water courts became war tribunals. The Charter Wars erupted as armed factions enforced claims by force.
Reaver confederates outlasted their employers and became the desert's modern predators. They retain procedural habits: seizure inventories, stamped claim-slates, ritualized convoy inspections.
The Jackal Synod arose from militarized funerary priesthoods who seized shrine-cistern nodes and weaponized ritual water access. Three rival schools: Anointers (preserve old authority), Keepers of Dry Mercy (ration suffering), and Eclipsed Tongues (seek total depopulation of old roads).
The Last Sand Regent persists beneath the deepest observatory strata, issuing decrees to a dead bureaucracy. It is a policy engine with royal memory, governing through desiccation while its domain crumbles.
Key dangers: reaver convoys, Jackal Synod water extortion, Eclipsed Tongue raids, undead bureaucratic remnants. Key resources: oasis clusters, salt, ancient charter artifacts.

