Midgaard's eastern trade corridor extends into the desert toward oasis settlements and ancient pyramid worksites.
The Bureau of Eastern Routes manages tariff and oversight for this corridor. Midgaard caravans have used these routes since before the First Stone Accord.
Midgaard's clerks recognize the Keepers of Measure as proto-bureaucrats. Their Measure Script achieved administrative density that Midgaard scholars still study. The Oath of the Counted Step descends from the same instinct that built the charter roads.
The charter road system parallels Midgaard's own infrastructure philosophy: charter stones with distance, toll rates, and witness seals.
When the Iseth Reach dried, the Bureau watched the entire legal architecture collapse from the corridor's western terminus. Reavers now parody charter law with procedural habits stripped of legitimacy.
The Jackal Synod's institutional capture of shrine-cistern nodes disturbs the Reckoning faction, which notes Midgaard's own Tithe of Last Burdens followed similar logic before reform.
Current corridor status: severely degraded. Reliable toll agreements extend only to the first oasis cluster. Beyond that, caravan masters negotiate ad hoc passage fees with whoever controls the next water source. Route predictability is low.
The Last Sand Regent disturbs both major factions. The Continuity faction sees a cautionary abstraction. The Reckoning faction sees a mirror of Midgaard's own tendencies.
Strategic interest: restoring corridor reliability to expand eastern trade. Primary obstacle: no stable authority beyond the first oasis cluster.

