Rakuen views the eastern desert as a mirror of governance built on measured scarcity rather than shared surplus.
The Keepers of Measure built civilization on calibration: every drop accounted for, every thirst measured. The Garden Ledger Clerks recognize a familiar sin in an unfamiliar face.
Elys Savan founded Rakuen on shared surplus. The Keepers founded their order on measured scarcity. Both recognized water is too important for markets and warlords, but diverged at the root. Rakuen chose trust in community sharing. The Keepers chose trust in instruments.
The Salt Ledger Kingdoms represent what Midgaard aspires to become: governance as audit, legitimacy as balanced ledger, citizens as line items in a water-debt register.
When the Iseth Reach dried, the Keepers' measured system became measured cruelty. The Charter Wars proved the Bloom Pavilion's argument: a system that measures people will eventually measure their right to live.
The Jackal Synod warns the Ember Wardens that governance built on scarcity turns every crisis into rationing of mercy.
The Last Sand Regent is called the Midgaard Prophecy by Garden Ledger Clerks. Not literal desiccation, but any system valuing its own continuity over the lives it governs will eventually govern nothing but its own records.
Rakuen's counter-notation: a flower beside a name, meaning someone was fed and nobody wrote down the cost. The desert is what governance becomes when it forgets people are not entries in a water-debt register.
Rakuen cracked because mountains fell on it, not because its own instruments turned against its people. This distinction matters.

